<div class="page">
  <div class="card">

    <div class="eyebrow">Start here</div>
    <div class="amber-rule"></div>
    <h1 class="h-title">How to read this operating model.</h1>
    <p class="h-sub">This model is <strong>intentionally information-rich</strong>. It is built to be clicked around, not read top-to-bottom. This page tells you where to start, what to expect and which parts will be most useful to you.</p>

    <!-- 30-second answer -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">In 30 seconds</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">What this is and what it isn't.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">The navigable reference for Martin and SLT&apos;s future-state vision for HomeTest. It holds the architecture, the cast, the open questions, the lifecycle and the human stories. <strong>The vision is the idea</strong> — what the service has to be to work at scale by 2030. This artefact is how you explore it, by question, by audience, by configuration.</p>

      <div class="three-up">
        <div class="what-tile">
          <div class="what-tile-h">What this is</div>
          <div class="what-tile-body">The navigable reference for Martin&apos;s future-state vision. A set of interconnected pages organised around five questions, with the people who run the service threaded through every one. Built to be explored, not read.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="what-tile">
          <div class="what-tile-h">What this isn't</div>
          <div class="what-tile-body">Not a static document, not a deck, not a delivery plan. It feeds them — the Hearts and Minds decks, the playbooks, the position papers and the prioritised delivery items all derive from it. A traditional operating model is a point-in-time snapshot. The snapshot is one of the outputs this produces.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="what-tile">
          <div class="what-tile-h">Who it's for</div>
          <div class="what-tile-body">NHSE colleagues, sponsors, commissioners, suppliers and clinicians. Anyone who needs to understand what the home-testing service has to be in order to work.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Shape -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">The shape</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">Every operating model answers five questions.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">This one is organised around them explicitly, with <strong>Why at the centre</strong>. The other four sit around it. Three further layers (Hearts and Minds, Status, Teamwork) wrap the five.</p>

      <div class="shape-wrap">
        <div class="shape-circle">
          <div class="shape-centre">
            <div class="shape-centre-q">Why</div>
            <div class="shape-centre-cap">PURPOSE</div>
          </div>
          <div class="shape-pet p-top">
            <div class="shape-pet-q">What</div>
            <div class="shape-pet-cap">ARCHITECTURE</div>
          </div>
          <div class="shape-pet p-right">
            <div class="shape-pet-q">When</div>
            <div class="shape-pet-cap">LIFECYCLE</div>
          </div>
          <div class="shape-pet p-bottom">
            <div class="shape-pet-q">How</div>
            <div class="shape-pet-cap">OPERATIONS</div>
          </div>
          <div class="shape-pet p-left">
            <div class="shape-pet-q">Who</div>
            <div class="shape-pet-cap">GOVERNANCE</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="shape-list">
          <div class="item"><span class="icon dark">W</span><strong>Why</strong> — the case for change. Four north stars that hold simultaneously.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon">W</span><strong>What</strong> — the architecture. Foundation, overlays, patterns, configurations.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon">W</span><strong>When</strong> — the lifecycle. Five stages, with a continuous-improvement loop.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon">H</span><strong>How</strong> — the operational pattern. Day-to-day swim lanes for each actor.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon">W</span><strong>Who</strong> — governance and accountability. RACI threaded through the cast.</div>
          <div class="item" style="margin-top:18px;padding-top:14px;border-top:1px dashed var(--border-lt);"><span class="icon pink">+</span><strong>Hearts and Minds</strong> — the human stories. How this walks into a room.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon amber">+</span><strong>Status</strong> — what is decided, what is in flight, what is open.</div>
          <div class="item"><span class="icon green">+</span><strong>Teamwork</strong> — the capability map. What it takes to run in BAU.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Where to start -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Where to start</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">Recommended reading order.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">If you have 40 minutes and want the model end to end, walk these six tiles in order. If you only have five minutes, open the second one (Hearts and Minds) and stop there. The model is built to be re-entered.</p>

      <div class="start-grid">

        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Why.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">1</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">5 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">Open with Why.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">The case for change. The four north stars that have to hold simultaneously. Read this first. Everything else makes more sense afterwards.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Hearts and Minds.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">2</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">5 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">Open Hearts and Minds.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">The human layer of the model. Four patient journeys — three across the initiation patterns (CVKM, PSA-AS, anaemia) and a fourth as the access-story carrier that runs underneath them. Pick whichever resonates. Each is a four-act read and any one of them is the five minutes.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Anatomical.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">3</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">10 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">Walk the architecture on What.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">Foundation, overlays, patterns, configurations. Four levels showing how the model is reusable across products. Click any pill to drill into the overlay detail.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="home.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">4</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">10 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">Click through the cast.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">Every person on the model has their own page with their pitch, what matters to them and where they sit. Skim the personas to see how the architecture lands on real roles.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Status.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">5</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">10 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">Open Status and Teamwork.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">Status is the honest list of what is open. Teamwork is the capability map and BAU sizing. The list is not the failure. The list is the structure that makes the questions answerable.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Prioritisation Framework.html" class="start-tile">
          <div class="start-num">6</div>
          <div class="start-body">
            <div class="start-mins">Optional &middot; 5 minutes</div>
            <div class="start-head">The Prioritisation Framework.</div>
            <div class="start-desc">The lens we use to choose what we build next. Five patterns, four tiers, a scoring construct. Endorsed by the Programme Board on 9 June 2026. Optional read; explains the logic behind the configurations.</div>
          </div>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Audiences -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Different readers find different things</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">If you have a specific question.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">The model is built to serve more than one audience. Pick the entry point closest to your role.</p>

      <div class="aud-grid">
        <div class="aud-card">
          <div class="aud-card-h">Sponsor / SLT</div>
          <div class="aud-card-body">Case for change, what is open, and BAU shape. Start with <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Why.html">Why</a>, then <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Hearts and Minds.html">Hearts and Minds</a>, then <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Status.html">Status</a> and <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Teamwork.html">Teamwork</a>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="aud-card">
          <div class="aud-card-h">Commissioner</div>
          <div class="aud-card-body">The recipe per configuration. Start with <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Sarah.html">Sarah's persona</a>, then the <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Pattern Overlay Detail.html">Pattern Overlay Detail</a>. The Commissioning overlay is where the funding question sits.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="aud-card">
          <div class="aud-card-h">Clinician</div>
          <div class="aud-card-body">The operational shape and how the model fits the clinical pathway. Start with <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Adam.html">Adam</a> (consultant) or <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Hannah.html">Hannah</a> (GP), then <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Operational.html">How</a>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="aud-card">
          <div class="aud-card-h">Supplier</div>
          <div class="aud-card-body">Where suppliers plug in. Start with <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Joe.html">Joe's persona</a>, then the foundation and overlays on <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Anatomical.html">What</a>. The platform-as-matchmaker frame matters here.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Honest expectations -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">What to expect</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">Three honest notes before you click in.</h2>

      <div class="honest">
        <p><strong>The model is information-rich on purpose.</strong> You are not meant to read it linearly. Click around. Open something. Follow the cross-links. Come back to this page if you get lost.</p>
        <p><strong>Status and Teamwork are honest about what is not yet known.</strong> The list of open decisions is long because the work is mid-flight. The list is not the failure. It is the structure that makes the open questions answerable.</p>
        <p><strong>Hearts and Minds is the human layer.</strong> Four patient journeys, one per pattern, told in four acts each. If you want a five-minute version of the whole model, open any of them. The layer is the reason this work became a labour of love.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="cta">
      <div class="cta-text">
        <div class="cta-text-h">Ready?</div>
        <div class="cta-text-body">The home page gives you the full set of doors into the model, the live status counts and the full cast. Bookmark it if you want to come back. This reading guide will stay here as a refresher.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-btns">
        <a href="home.html" class="cta-btn-main">Take me to the home page &rarr;</a>
        <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Why.html" class="cta-btn-sec">Or open Why first &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="foot">
      HomeTest Operating Model &middot; Reading guide &middot; The model is the centre of the work. This page is the on-ramp.
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

</body>
</html>
